                    <marginalia_text>
                        Iuvat h&icirc;c memorabilem C. Taciti locum transscribere, ex Annalium l. 3.
                        Pulso Tarquinio, advers&ugrave;m Patrum factiones multa Populus parauit tuenda[e] Libertatis, et firmanda[e] Concordia[e]: creatiq[ue] Decemuiri; 
                        et accitis, qua[e] vsq[uam] egregia, composita[e] duodecim tabula[e]; finis a[e]qui iuris. Censura Romanarum Legum, observatu digna cum primis. 
                        XII. Tabularum compositio, finis a[e]qui iuris. Quid it&agrave;? ratio seria, et adhuc momentosa. Nam secutae Leges, etsi aliquando in maleficos ex delicto; 
                        sa[e]pi&ugrave;s tamen dissensione ordinum, et apiscendi illicitos honores, aut pellendi claros viros, aliaq[ue] ob prava per vim lata[e] sunt. 
                        Vin’ ipsa exempla? Hinc Gracchi, et Saturnini, turbatores plebis: nec minor largitor nomine senatus Drusus: corrupti spe, 
                        aut illusi per intercessionem socij.
                    </marginalia_text> <!--JG: Impossible to know exactly whom Harvey meant with the Saturni and Drusus-->
                    <person name="Tacitus"/>
                    <person name="Tarquinius Superbus"/>
                    <person name="Tiberius Gracchus"/>
                    <person name="Gaius Gracchus"/>
                    <book title="Annals"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>It is useful here to copy a remarkable passage of Cornelius Tacitus, from bk 3 of the Annals:
                “After Tarquin's expulsion, the people, to check cabals among the Senators, devised many safeguards for freedom and for the establishment of unity. 
                Decemvirs were appointed; everything specially admirable elsewhere was adopted, and the Twelve Tables drawn up, the last specimen of equitable 
                legislation.” His review of the Roman laws is particularly noteworthy. The composition of the Twelve Tables was the last specimen of equitable 
                legislation: Why so? There is a serious and still weighty reason: “For subsequent enactments, though occasionally directed against evildoers 
                for some crime, were oftener carried by violence amid class dissensions, with a view to obtain honours not as yet conceded, or to banish 
                distinguished citizens, or for other base ends.” Do you want the very examples? “Hence the Gracchi and Saturnini, those popular agitators, 
                and Drusus too, as flagrant a corrupter in the Senate's name; hence, the bribing of our allies by alluring promises and the cheating them by 
                tribunes vetoes.” 
            </translation> <!--What do we do with the source of the translation that ABO includes: [Transl. Tacitus by Jackson and Brodribb]. How/where do we cite our sources??-->
        </marginalia>
        
